# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: delaware
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:delaware/1790-united-states-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:delaware/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:delaware/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:delaware/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:delaware/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:delaware/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:delaware/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:delaware/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:delaware/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:delaware/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:delaware/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:delaware/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:delaware/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:delaware/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:delaware/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:delaware/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:delaware/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:delaware/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:delaware/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:delaware/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:delaware/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:delaware/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:delaware/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:delaware/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:delaware/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:delaware/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:delaware/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:delaware/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:delaware/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:delaware/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:delaware/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:delaware/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:delaware/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:delaware/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:delaware/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:delaware/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:delaware/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:delaware/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:delaware/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:delaware/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:delaware/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:delaware/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:delaware/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:delaware/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:delaware/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:delaware/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:delaware/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:delaware/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:delaware/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:delaware/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:delaware/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:delaware/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:delaware/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:delaware/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:delaware/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:delaware/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:delaware/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:delaware/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:delaware/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware occupies the northeastern portion of the Delmarva Peninsula, and some islands and territory within the Delaware River.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] It is the second-smallest and sixth-least populous state, but also the sixth-most densely populated.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware's most populous city is Wilmington, and the state's capital is Dover, the second-most populous city in Delaware.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The state is divided into three counties, the fewest number of counties of any of the 50 U.S. states; from north to south, the three counties are: New Castle County, Kent County, and Sussex County.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The southern two counties, Kent and Sussex, have historically been predominantly agrarian economies.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] New Castle is more urbanized and is considered part of the Philadelphia metropolitan area.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware is considered part of the Southern United States by the U.S.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Census Bureau, but the state's geography, culture, and history are a hybrid of the Mid-Atlantic, Northeastern, and Southern regions of the country.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Before the Delaware coastline was explored and developed by Europeans in the 17th century, the state was inhabited by several Native American tribes, including the Lenape in the north and Nanticoke in the south.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The state was first colonized by Dutch traders at Zwaanendael, near present-day Lewes, Delaware, in 1631.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware was one of the Thirteen Colonies that participated in the American Revolution against Great Britain, which established the United States as an independent nation.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] On December 7, 1787, Delaware was the first state to ratify the Constitution of the United States, earning it the nickname "The First State".
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Since the turn of the 20th century, Delaware has become an onshore corporate haven whose corporate laws are deemed appealing to corporations; over half of all New York Stock Exchange-listed corporations and over three-fifths of the *Fortune* 500 are legally incorporated in Delaware.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Over 90% of all U.S. based companies that went public in 2021 incorporated themselves in Delaware.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware was named after its location on the Delaware Bay, which in turn derived its name from Thomas West, 3rd Baron De La Warr (1577–1618), the first governor of the Colony of Virginia.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The Delaware people, a name used by Europeans for Lenape people Indigenous to the Delaware Valley, also derive their name from the same source.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The name *de La Warr* was derived from Sussex and is of Anglo-French origin.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] It came probably from a Norman lieu-dit *La Guerre*.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] This toponymic likely derived from Latin *ager*, the Breton *gwern* or from the Late Latin *varectum* (fallow).
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The toponyms Gara, Gare, Gaire, (the sound [ä] often mutated in [æ]) also appear in historical texts cited by Lucien Musset, where the word *ga(i)ra* means gore.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] It could also be linked with a patronymic from the Old Norse *verr*.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Before Delaware was settled by European colonists, the present-day state was home to the Eastern Algonquian tribes known as the Unami Lenape, or Delaware, who lived mostly along the coast, and the Nanticoke who occupied much of the southern Delmarva Peninsula.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] John Smith also showed two Iroquoian tribes, the Kuskarawock and Tockwogh, living north of the Nanticoke—they may have held small portions of land in the western part of the state before migrating across the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The Kuskarawocks were most likely the Tuscarora.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The Unami Lenape in the Delaware Valley were closely related to Munsee Lenape tribes along the Hudson River.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] They had a settled hunting and agricultural society, and they rapidly became middlemen in an increasingly frantic fur trade with their ancient enemy, the Minqua or Susquehannock.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] With the loss of their lands on the Delaware River and the destruction of the Minqua by the Iroquois of the Five Nations in the 1670s, the remnants of the Lenape who wished to remain identified as such left the region and moved over the Allegheny Mountains by the mid-18th century.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The Dutch were the first Europeans to settle in present-day Delaware in the middle region by establishing a trading post at Zwaanendael, near the site of Lewes in 1631.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Within a year, all the settlers were killed in a dispute with Native American tribes living in the area.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In 1638, New Sweden, a Swedish trading post and colony, was established at Fort Christina (now in Wilmington) by Peter Minuit at the head of a group of Swedes, Finns and Dutch.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The colony of New Sweden lasted 17 years.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In 1651, the Dutch, reinvigorated by the leadership of Peter Stuyvesant, established a fort at present-day New Castle and, in 1655, they conquered the New Sweden colony, annexing it into the Dutch New Netherland.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Only nine years later, in 1664, the Dutch were conquered by a fleet of English ships by Sir Robert Carr under the direction of James, the Duke of York.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Fighting off a prior claim by Cecil Calvert, 2nd Baron Baltimore, Proprietor of Maryland, the Duke passed his somewhat dubious ownership on to William Penn in 1682.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Penn strongly desired access to the sea for his Pennsylvania province and leased what then came to be known as the "Lower Counties on the Delaware" from the Duke.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Penn established representative government and briefly combined his two possessions under one General Assembly in 1682.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] However, by 1704 the province of Pennsylvania had grown so large their representatives wanted to make decisions without the assent of the Lower Counties, and the two groups of representatives began meeting on their own, one at Philadelphia, and the other at New Castle.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Penn and his heirs remained proprietors of both and always appointed the same person Governor for their province of Pennsylvania and their territory of the Lower Counties.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The fact that Delaware and Pennsylvania shared the same governor was not unique; from 1703 to 1738, New York and New Jersey shared a governor.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Massachusetts and New Hampshire also shared a governor for some time.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Dependent in early years on indentured labor, Delaware imported more slaves as the number of English immigrants decreased with better economic conditions in England.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The colony became a slave society and cultivated tobacco as a cash crop, although English immigrants continued to arrive.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Like the other middle colonies, the Lower Counties on the Delaware initially showed little enthusiasm for a break with Britain.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The citizenry had a good relationship with the Proprietary government, and generally were allowed more independence of action in their Colonial Assembly than in other colonies.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Merchants at the port of Wilmington had trading ties with the British.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] New Castle lawyer Thomas McKean denounced the Stamp Act in the strongest terms, and Kent County native John Dickinson became the "Penman of the Revolution".
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Anticipating the Declaration of Independence, Patriot leaders Thomas McKean and Caesar Rodney convinced the Colonial Assembly to declare itself separated from British and Pennsylvania rule on June 15, 1776.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The person best representing Delaware's majority, George Read, could not bring himself to vote for a Declaration of Independence.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Only the dramatic overnight ride of Caesar Rodney gave the delegation the votes needed to cast Delaware's vote for independence.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Initially led by John Haslet, Delaware provided one of the premier regiments in the Continental Army, known as the "Delaware Blues" and nicknamed the "Blue Hen's Chicks".
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In August 1777 General Sir William Howe led a British army through Delaware on his way to a victory at the Battle of Brandywine and capture of the city of Philadelphia.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The only real engagement on Delaware soil was the Battle of Cooch's Bridge, fought on September 3, 1777, at Cooch's Bridge in New Castle County, although there was a minor Loyalist rebellion in 1778.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Following the Battle of Brandywine, Wilmington was occupied by the British, and State President John McKinly was taken prisoner.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The British remained in control of the Delaware River for much of the rest of the war, disrupting commerce and providing encouragement to an active Loyalist portion of the population, particularly in Sussex County.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Because the British promised slaves of rebels freedom for fighting with them, escaped slaves flocked north to join their lines.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Following the American Revolution, statesmen from Delaware were among the leading proponents of a strong central United States with equal representation for each state.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Many colonial settlers came to Delaware from Maryland and Virginia, where the population had been increasing rapidly.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The economies of these colonies were chiefly based on labor-intensive tobacco and increasingly dependent on African slaves because of a decline in working class immigrants from England.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Most of the English colonists had arrived as indentured servants (contracted for a fixed period to pay for their passage), and in the early years the line between servant and slave was fluid.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Most of the free African-American families in Delaware before the Revolution had migrated from Maryland to find more affordable land.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] They were descendants chiefly of relationships or marriages between white servant women and enslaved, servant or free African or African-American men.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Under slavery law, children took the social status of their mothers, so children born to white women were free, regardless of their paternity, just as children born to enslaved women were born into slavery.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] As the flow of indentured laborers to the colony decreased with improving economic conditions in England, more slaves were imported for labor and the caste lines hardened.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] By the end of the colonial period, the number of enslaved people in Delaware began to decline.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Shifts in the agriculture economy from tobacco to mixed farming resulted in less need for slaves' labor.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In addition local Methodists and Quakers encouraged slaveholders to free their slaves following the American Revolution, and many did so in a surge of individual manumissions for idealistic reasons.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] By 1810, three-quarters of all blacks in Delaware were free.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] When John Dickinson freed his slaves in 1777, he was Delaware's largest slave owner with 37 slaves.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In 1840, Delaware's population was 78,085 of whom 2,605 were slaves.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] By 1860, the largest slaveholder owned 16 slaves.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Although an attempt to abolish slavery in 1847 failed by narrow margins in the legislature, the percentage of Delaware's Black population held as slaves decreased over time.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] By the 1860 census on the verge of the Civil War, 91.7% of the black population were free; 1,798 were slaves, as compared to 19,829 "free colored persons".
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] An independent black denomination was chartered in 1813 by freed slave Peter Spencer as the "Union Church of Africans".
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] This followed the 1793 establishment in Philadelphia of the African Methodist Episcopal Church by Richard Allen, which had ties to the Methodist Episcopal Church until 1816.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Spencer built a church in Wilmington for the new denomination.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] This was renamed as the African Union First Colored Methodist Protestant Church and Connection, more commonly known as the A.U.M.P.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In 1814, Spencer called for the first annual gathering, known as the Big August Quarterly, which continues to draw members of this denomination and their descendants together in a religious and cultural festival.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] During the secession crisis of late 1860 - early 1861, the Southern states sent commissioners to try to convince the legislature to join Delaware's fellow slave states and leave the Union.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] However, the state lawmakers opposed secession due to Delaware's geographic vulnerability and economic ties to the North, and on January 3, 1861 they passed a resolution condemning secession.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] While most Delaware citizens who fought in the war served in the Union army, some served in companies on the Confederate side in Maryland and Virginia Regiments.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware is notable for being the only slave state from which no Confederate regiments or militia groups were assembled.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware's wartime government was dominated by pro-slavery Democrats, and in February 1865 the legislature voted to reject the 13th Amendment which abolished slavery.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The 14th Amendment, granting citizenship to Black Americans, and the 15th Amendment, granting voting rights, were similarly rejected, but became effective nationwide when a majority of states approved them.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The state then enacted Jim Crow laws in the 1870s that would establish legal racial discrimination until the 1960s.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware officially ratified the 13th, 14th, and 15th amendments on February 12, 1901, decades after they had already come into force.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] During the Reconstruction Era that followed the Civil War, Democratic Redeemer governments led by the South's Bourbon aristocracy continued to dominate the region and imposed explicitly white supremacist regimes in the former slave states.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The Delaware legislature declared Black people to be second-class citizens in 1866, and restricted their voting rights despite the 15th Amendment, ensuring continued Democratic success in the state throughout most of the 19th century.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Fearful that the 1875 Civil Rights Act passed by Congress might establish racial equality, Delaware legislators passed Jim Crow laws that mandated segregation in public facilities.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The state's educational system was segregated by operation of law.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Beginning in the late 19th century, the Wilmington area grew into a manufacturing center.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Investment in manufacturing in the city grew from $5.5 million in 1860 to $44 million in 1900.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The most notable manufacturer in the state was the chemical company DuPont, which to this day is heavily credited with making the state what it is today in many ways.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Because of Wilmington's growth, local politicians from the city and New Castle County pressured the state government to adopt a new constitution providing the north with more representation.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] However, the subsequent 1897 constitution did not proportionally represent the north and continued to give the southern counties disproportionate influence.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] As manufacturing expanded, businesses became major players in state affairs and funders of politicians through families such as the Du Ponts.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Republican John Addicks attempted to buy a US Senate seat multiple times in a rivalry with the Du Ponts until the passage of the 17th Amendment.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The allegiance of industries with the Republican party allowed them to gain control of the state's governorship throughout most of the 20th century.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The GOP ensured black people could vote because of their general support for Republicans and thus undid restrictions on Black suffrage.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware benefited greatly from World War I because of the state's large gunpowder industry.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] DuPont, the most dominant business in the state by WWI, produced an estimated 40% of all gunpowder used by the Allies during the war.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] It produced nylon in the state after the war and began investments into General Motors.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Additionally, the company invested heavily in the expansion of public schools in the state and colleges such as the University of Delaware in the 1910s and 1920s.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] This included primary and secondary schools for Black people and women.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware suffered less during the Great Depression than other states, but the depression spurred further migration from the rural south to urban areas.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Like in World War I, the state enjoyed a big stimulus to its gunpowder and shipyard industries in World War II.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] New job opportunities during and after the war in the Wilmington area coaxed Black people from the southern counties to move to the city.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The proportion of blacks constituting the city's population rose from 15% in 1950 to over 50% by 1980.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The surge of Black migrants to the north sparked white flight, in which middle class whites moved from the city to suburban areas, leading to *de facto* segregation of Northern Delaware's society.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In the 1940s and 1950s, Delaware attempted to integrate its schools, although the last segregated school in the state did not close until 1970.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The University of Delaware admitted its first black student in 1948, and local courts ruled that primary schools had to be integrated.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware's integration efforts partially inspired the US Supreme Court's decision in *Brown v.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Board of Education*, which found racial segregation in United States public schools to be unconstitutional.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The result of the *Brown* ruling was that Delaware became fully integrated, albeit with time and much effort.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In October 1954, the city of Milford became the scene of one of the country's first pro-segregation boycotts after eleven Black students were enrolled in the previously all-white Milford High School.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Mass protests continued in Milford; the school board eventually ceded to the protestors, expelling the Black students.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The ensuing unrest, which included cross burnings, rallies, and pro-segregation demonstrations, contributed to desegregation in most of Southern Delaware being delayed for another ten years.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Sussex County did not start closing or integrating its segregated schools until 1965, 11 years after the *Brown* ruling.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Throughout the state, integration only encouraged more white flight, and poor economic conditions for the black population led to some violence during the 1960s.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Riots broke out in Wilmington in 1967 and again in 1968 in response to the assassination of Martin Luther King Jr, after which the National Guard occupied the city for nine months to prevent further violence.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Since WWII, the state has been generally economically prosperous and enjoyed relatively high per capita income because of its location between major cities like Philadelphia, New York, and Washington, DC.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Its population grew rapidly, particularly in the suburbs in the north where New Castle county became an extension of the Philadelphia metropolitan area.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Americans, including migrants from Puerto Rico, and immigrants from Latin America flocked to the state.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] By 1990, only 50% of Delaware's population consisted of natives to the state.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware is 96 miles (154 km) long and ranges from 9 to 35 miles (14 to 56 km) across, with a land area of 1,982 square miles (5,130 km2) and a total area of 2,489 square miles (6,450 km2), making it the second-smallest state by either metric in the United States after Rhode Island.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware is bounded to the north by Pennsylvania; to the east by the Delaware River, Delaware Bay, New Jersey, and the Atlantic Ocean; and to the west and south by Maryland.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Small portions of Delaware are also situated on the eastern side of the Delaware River sharing land boundaries with New Jersey.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The state of Delaware, together with the Eastern Shore counties of Maryland and two counties of Virginia, form the Delmarva Peninsula, which stretches down the Mid-Atlantic Coast.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The definition of the northern boundary of the state is unusual.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Most of the boundary between Delaware and Pennsylvania was originally defined by an arc extending 12 miles (19.3 km) from the cupola of the courthouse in the city of New Castle.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] This boundary is often referred to as the Twelve-Mile Circle.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Although the Twelve-Mile Circle is often claimed to be the only territorial boundary in the U.S. that is a true arc, the Mexican boundary with Texas includes several arcs, and many cities in the South (such as Plains, Georgia) also have circular boundaries.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] On the west, Delaware and Maryland are mostly separated by a line running from the midpoint of the Transpeninsular Line, going slightly west of due north up to its tangent point on the Twelve-Mile Circle.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The border follows the Circle for a short distance and then continues in a straight line due north until reaching the southern border of Pennsylvania.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The Wedge of land between the northwest part of the arc and the Maryland border was claimed by both Delaware and Pennsylvania until 1921, when Delaware's claim was confirmed.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware is on a level plain, with the lowest mean elevation of any state in the nation.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Its highest elevation, located at Ebright Azimuth, near Concord High School, is less than 450 feet (140 m) above sea level.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The northernmost part of the state is part of the Piedmont Plateau with hills and rolling surfaces.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The Atlantic Seaboard fall line approximately follows the Robert Kirkwood Highway between Newark and Wilmington; south of this road is the Atlantic Coastal Plain with flat, sandy, and, in some parts, swampy ground.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] A ridge about 75 to 80 feet (23 to 24 m) high extends along the western boundary of the state and separates the watersheds that feed Delaware River and Bay to the east and the Chesapeake Bay to the west.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Since almost all of Delaware is a part of the Atlantic coastal plain, the effects of the ocean moderate its climate.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The state lies in the humid subtropical climate (Köppen *Cfa*) zone.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Despite its small size (roughly 100 miles (160 km) from its northernmost to southernmost points), there is significant variation in mean temperature and amount of snowfall between Sussex County and New Castle County.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Moderated by the Atlantic Ocean and Delaware Bay, the southern portion of the state has a milder climate and a longer growing season than the northern portion of the state.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Summers are long, hot, and humid in Delaware, often with intense (but brief) late day thundershowers.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware averages 2,300 hrs of sunshine annually (higher than the USA average).
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Winters are modestly cool to cold in northern Delaware, and cool to mild in southern Delaware.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The normal seasonal snowfall ranges from about 20.0 inches in Wilmington to only 10.0 inches in Lewes.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In many winters no snow will fall in coastal Delaware.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Northern Delaware falls into USDA Garden Zone 7a, while southern and coastal areas fall into USDA zone 7b and 8a.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The milder climate in southern Delaware allows for subtropical flora such as the windmill palm, needle palm, and dwarf palmetto.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware's all-time record high of 110 °F (43 °C) was recorded at Millsboro on July 21, 1930.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The all-time record low of −17 °F (−27 °C) was also recorded at Millsboro, on January 17, 1893.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The hardiness zones are 7B and 8A at the Delaware Beaches.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The transitional climate of Delaware supports a wide variety of vegetation.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In the northern third of the state are found Northeastern coastal forests and mixed oak forests typical of the northeastern United States.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In the southern two-thirds of the state are found Middle Atlantic coastal forests.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Trap Pond State Park, along with areas in other parts of Sussex County, for example, support the northernmost stands of bald cypress trees in North America.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware provides government subsidy support for the clean-up of property "lightly contaminated" by hazardous waste, the proceeds for which come from a tax on wholesale petroleum sales.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Wilmington is the state's most populous city (70,635) and its economic hub.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] It is located within commuting distance of both Philadelphia and Baltimore.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Dover is the state capital and the second most populous city (38,079).
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The table below lists the ten largest municipalities in the state based on the 2020 United States census.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The United States Census Bureau determined that the population of Delaware was 989,948 on April 1, 2020, an increase from the 2010 census figure of 897,934.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware's history as a border state has led it to exhibit characteristics of both the Northern and the Southern regions of the United States.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Census Bureau designates Delaware as one of the South Atlantic States, but it is commonly associated with the Mid-Atlantic States or northeastern United States by other federal agencies, the media, and some residents.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware is the sixth most densely populated state, with a population density of 442.6 people per square mile, 356.4 per square mile more than the national average, and ranking 45th in population.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware is one of five U.S. states (Maine, Vermont, West Virginia, Wyoming) that do not have a single city with a population over 100,000 as of the 2010 census.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The center of population of Delaware is in New Castle County, in the town of Townsend.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] According to HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 2,369 homeless people in Delaware.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] People of Hispanic or Latino origin, of any race, made up 8.2% of the population.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The 2022 American Community Survey estimated the state had a racial and ethnic makeup of 60.6% non-Hispanic whites, 23.6% Black or African American, 0.7% American Indian or Alaska Native, 4.2% Asian, 0.1% Pacific Islander, 2.9% multiracial, and 10.1% Hispanic or Latin American of any race.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Historical Indigenous tribes include the Nanticoke as well as the Lenape, who were influential in the colonial period of the United States.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] A state-recognized tribe called the Lenape Indian Tribe of Delaware is headquartered in Cheswold, Kent County, Delaware.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Another state-recognized tribe called the Nanticoke Indian Association resides in Sussex County and is headquartered in Millsboro, Sussex County, Delaware.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Along with an off-shoot group, the state-recognized Nanticoke Lenni-Lenape Tribal Nation in New Jersey, these three state-recognized tribes in Delaware and New Jersey are descended from the Delaware Moors.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The Delaware Moors are a mixed-race group who live in and around Cheswold and Millsboro in Delaware, as well as Gouldtown, New Jersey.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The Delaware Moors were legally classified as African Americans until 1914, when the State of Delaware reclassified them as a separate, non-Black group.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In the 2020 Census, 218,899 Delaware residents were identified as African American (of the total 989,948).
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In 2 of the state's 3 counties, African Americans make up more than 20% of the population: Kent (25.8%) and New Castle (25.7%).
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] African Americans in the seven counties of New Castle (146,544), Kent (46,998), and Sussex (25,357) make up more than 100% of all African Americans in the state.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware's population mainly consisted of people from the British Isles, African slaves, Germans and a few remaining Native Americans during the colonial era.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Irish, Germans, Italians, Poles, and Russian Jewish immigrants were attracted by the industries in the Wilmington area.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In the late 20th century a Puerto Rican community formed in Wilmington.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Guatemalan people migrated to Sussex county to work in Delaware's poultry industry.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] There is also a small numbers of Asians in New Castle county who work as scientific and engineering professionals.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The top countries of origin for Delaware's immigrants in 2018 were Mexico, India, Guatemala, China, and Jamaica.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In 2000, 91% of Delaware residents of age 5 and older spoke only English at home; 5% spoke Spanish.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] French was the third most spoken language, used by 0.7% of the population, followed by Chinese (0.5%) and German (0.5%).
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Legislation has been proposed in both the House and the Senate in Delaware to designate English as the official language.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Neither bill was passed in the legislature.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] A 2012 Gallup poll found that Delaware's proportion of lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender adults stood at 3.4% of the population.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] This constitutes a total LGBT adult population estimate of 23,698 people.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The number of same-sex couple households in 2010 stood at 2,646.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] This grew by 41.65% from a decade earlier.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] On July 1, 2013, same-sex marriage was legalized, and all civil unions were converted into marriages.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The predominant religion practiced in Delaware is Christianity.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] A 2014 estimate by the Pew Research Center found that members of Protestant churches accounted for almost half of the population, though the Roman Catholic Church was the largest single denomination in the state.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] By 2020, the Public Religion Research Institute determined 61% of the population was Christian.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In 2022, the Public Religion Research Institute's survey revealed 60% were Christian, followed by Jews (3%), Hindus (1%), and New Agers (1%).
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In 2020, the Association of Religion Data Archives reported the largest Christian denominations were the Catholic Church with 197,094; non-denominational Protestants with 49,392, and United Methodists with 39,959.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The Roman Catholic Diocese of Wilmington and the Episcopal Diocese of Delaware oversee the parishes within their denominations.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Church, the oldest African-American denomination in the nation, was founded in Wilmington.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] It still has a substantial presence in the state.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Reflecting new immigrant populations, an Islamic mosque has been built in the Ogletown area, and a Hindu temple in Hockessin.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware is home to an Amish community which resides west of Dover in Kent County, consisting of nine church districts and about 1,650 people.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The Amish first settled in Kent County in 1915.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In recent years, increasing development has led to the decline in the number of Amish living in the community.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] A 2012 survey of religious attitudes in the United States found that 34% of Delaware residents considered themselves "moderately religious", 33% "very religious", and 33% as "non-religious".
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] At the 2014 Pew Research survey, 23% of the population were irreligious; the 2020 Public Religion Research Institute's survey determined 31% of the population were irreligious.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In 2022, the same study showed 33% of the population as irreligious.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] According to a 2020 study by Kiplinger, Delaware had the 17th most millionaires per capita in the United States; altogether, there were 25,937 such individuals.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The median income for Delaware households as of 2020 was $64,805.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware's agricultural output consists of poultry, nursery stock, soybeans, dairy products and corn.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] As of May 2025, the state's unemployment rate was 4.0%.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In 2025, 98.7% of the businesses in the state were small businesses and employed 50.6% of the state's work force.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In late 2015, DuPont announced that 1,700 employees, nearly a third of its footprint in Delaware, would be laid off in early 2016.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The merger of E.I. du Pont de Nemours & Co. and Dow Chemical Company into DowDuPont took place on September 1, 2017.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] More than half of all U.S. publicly traded companies, and 63% of the Fortune 500, are incorporated in Delaware.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The state's attractiveness as a corporate haven is largely because of its business-friendly corporation law.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Franchise taxes on Delaware corporations supply about a fifth of the state's revenue.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Although "USA (Delaware)" ranked as the world's most opaque jurisdiction on the Tax Justice Network's 2009 Financial Secrecy Index, the same group's 2011 Index ranks the U.S. fifth and does not specify Delaware.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In Delaware, there are more than a million registered corporations.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware ranked 4th for most businesses formed in 2025, with 327,103.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Title 4, chapter 7 of the Delaware Code stipulates that alcoholic liquor be sold only in specifically licensed establishments, and only between 9:00 a.m. and 1:00 a.m.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Until 2003, Delaware was among the several states enforcing blue laws and banned the sale of liquor on Sunday.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Two daily newspapers are based in Delaware, the *Delaware State News*, based in Dover and covering the two southern counties, and *The News Journal* covering Wilmington and northern Delaware.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The state is also served by several weekly, monthly and online publications.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] No standalone television stations are based solely in Delaware.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] The northern part of the state is served by network stations in Philadelphia and the southern part by network stations in Salisbury, Maryland.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Philadelphia's ABC affiliate, WPVI-TV, maintains a news bureau in downtown Wilmington.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Salisbury's CBS affiliate, WBOC-TV, maintains bureaus in Dover and Milton.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Three Philadelphia-market stations—PBS member WHYY-TV, Ion affiliate WPPX, and MeTV affiliate WDPN-TV—all have Wilmington as their city of license, but maintain transmitters at the market antenna farm in Roxborough, Philadelphia and do not produce any Delaware-centric programming.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] There are a numerous radio stations licensed in Delaware.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] WDOV 1410AM, WDSD 94.7 FM and WRTX 91.7 FM are licensed from Dover.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware has several museums, wildlife refuges, parks, houses, lighthouses, and other historic places.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Rehoboth Beach, together with the towns of Lewes, Dewey Beach, Bethany Beach, South Bethany, and Fenwick Island, comprise Delaware's beach resorts.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Rehoboth Beach often bills itself as "The Nation's Summer Capital" because it is a frequent summer vacation destination for Washington, D.C., residents as well as visitors from Maryland, Virginia, and in lesser numbers, Pennsylvania.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Vacationers are drawn for many reasons, including the town's charm, artistic appeal, nightlife, and tax-free shopping.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] According to SeaGrant Delaware, the Delaware beaches generate $6.9 billion annually and over $711 million in tax revenue.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware is home to several festivals, fairs, and events.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In 2015, tourism in Delaware generated $3.1 billion, which makes up five percent of the state's GDP.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware saw 8.5 million visitors in 2015, with the tourism industry employing 41,730 people, making it the 4th largest private employer in the state.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Major origin markets for Delaware tourists include Philadelphia, Baltimore, New York City, Washington, D.C., and Harrisburg, with 97% of tourists arriving to the state by car and 75% of tourists coming from a distance of 200 miles (320 km) or less.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Delaware is also home to two large sporting venues.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Dover Motor Speedway is a race track in Dover, and Frawley Stadium in Wilmington is the home of the Wilmington Blue Rocks, a Minor League Baseball team that is currently affiliated with the Washington Nationals.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In the early 1920s, Pierre S. du Pont served as president of the state board of education.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] At the time, state law prohibited money raised from white taxpayers from being used to support the state's schools for black children.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Appalled by the condition of the black schools, du Pont donated four million dollars to construct 86 new school buildings.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Gebhart* (1952), one of the four cases which were combined into *Brown v.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Board of Education*, the Supreme Court of the United States decision that led to the end of officially segregated public schools.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Significantly, *Belton* was the only case in which the state court found for the plaintiffs, thereby ruling that segregation is unconstitutional.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] Unlike many states, Delaware's educational system is centralized in a state Superintendent of Education, with local school boards retaining control over taxation and some curriculum decisions.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] This centralized system, combined with the small size of the state, likely contributed to Delaware becoming the first state, after completion of a three-year, $30 million program ending in 1999, to wire every K-12 classroom in the state to the Internet.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] As of 2011, the Delaware Department of Education had authorized the founding of 25 charter schools in the state, one of them being all-girls.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] In 2010, Delaware had the largest percentage of students attending private schools of places within the United States.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] All teachers in the State's public school districts are unionized.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] As of January 2012, none of the State's charter schools are members of a teachers union.
[src:delaware/delaware-p01] One of the State's teachers' unions is Delaware State Education Association (DSEA).
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The transportation system in Delaware is under the governance and supervision of the Delaware Department of Transportation (DelDOT).
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Funding for DelDOT projects is drawn, in part, from the Delaware Transportation Trust Fund, established in 1987 to help stabilize transportation funding; the availability of the Trust led to a gradual separation of DelDOT operations from other Delaware state operations.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] In 2009, DelDOT maintained 13,507 lane-miles, totaling 89 percent of the state's public roadway system, the rest being under the supervision of individual municipalities.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] This far exceeds the national average (20 percent) for state department of transportation maintenance responsibility.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Interstate Highway System, Interstate 95 (I-95), crosses Delaware southwest-to-northeast across New Castle County.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Two Auxiliary Interstate Highway routes are also located in the state.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Interstate 495 (I-495) is an eastern bypass of Wilmington.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Interstate 295 (I-295) is a bypass of Philadelphia which begins south of Wilmington.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] In addition to Interstate highways, there are six U.S. highways that serve Delaware: U.S.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] There are also several state highways that cross the state of Delaware; a few of them include DE 1, DE 9, and DE 404.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] 13 and DE 1 are primary north–south highways connecting Wilmington and Pennsylvania with Maryland, with DE 1 serving as the main route between Wilmington and the Delaware beaches.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] DE 9 is a north–south highway connecting Dover and Wilmington via a scenic route along the Delaware Bay.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] 40 is a primary east–west route, connecting Maryland with New Jersey.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] DE 404 is another primary east–west highway connecting the Chesapeake Bay Bridge in Maryland with the Delaware beaches.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The state also operates three toll highways, the Delaware Turnpike, which is I-95, between Maryland and New Castle; the Korean War Veterans Memorial Highway, which is DE 1, between Wilmington and Dover; and the U.S.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] 301 toll road between the Maryland border and DE 1 in New Castle County.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] A bicycle route, Delaware Bicycle Route 1, spans the north–south length of the state from the Maryland border in Fenwick Island to the Pennsylvania border north of Montchanin.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] It is the first of several signed bike routes planned in Delaware.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Delaware has about 875 bridges, 95 percent of which are under the supervision of DelDOT.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] About 30 percent of all Delaware bridges were built before 1950, and about 60 percent of the number are included in the National Bridge Inventory.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Some bridges not under DelDOT supervision includes the four bridges on the Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which are under the jurisdiction of the U.S.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Army Corps of Engineers, and the Delaware Memorial Bridge, which is under the bi-state Delaware River and Bay Authority.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] It has been noted that the tar and chip composition of secondary roads in Sussex County makes them more prone to deterioration than are the asphalt roadways in almost the rest of the state.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Among these roads, Sussex (county road) 236 is among the most problematic.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Amtrak has two stations in Delaware along the Northeast Corridor; the relatively quiet Newark Rail Station in Newark, and the busier Wilmington Station in Wilmington.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The Northeast Corridor is also served by SEPTA's Wilmington/Newark Line, part of SEPTA Regional Rail, which serves Claymont, Wilmington, Churchmans Crossing, and Newark.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Two Class I railroads, Norfolk Southern and CSX, provide freight rail service in northern New Castle County.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Norfolk Southern provides freight service along the Northeast Corridor and to industrial areas in Edgemoor, New Castle, and Delaware City.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] CSX's Philadelphia Subdivision passes through northern New Castle County parallel to the Amtrak Northeast Corridor.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Multiple short-line railroads provide freight service in Delaware.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The Delmarva Central Railroad connects with the Maryland and Delaware Railroad, which serves local customers in Sussex County.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] CSX connects with the freight/heritage operation, the Wilmington and Western Railroad, based in Wilmington and the East Penn Railroad, which operates a line from Wilmington to Coatesville, Pennsylvania.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The last north–south passenger trains through the main part of Delaware was the Pennsylvania Railroad's local Wilmington-Delmar train in 1965.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] This was a successor to the *Del-Mar-Va Express* and *Cavalier*, which had run from Philadelphia through the state's interior, to the end of the Delmarva Peninsula until the mid-1950s.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The DART First State public transportation system was named "Most Outstanding Public Transportation System" in 2003 by the American Public Transportation Association.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Coverage of the system is broad within northern New Castle County with close association to major highways in Kent and Sussex counties.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The system includes bus, subsidized passenger rail operated by Philadelphia transit agency SEPTA, and subsidized taxi and paratransit modes.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The paratransit system, consisting of a statewide door-to-door bus service for the elderly and disabled, has been described by a Delaware state report as "the most generous paratransit system in the United States".
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] As of 2012, fees for the paratransit service have not changed since 1988.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] As of 2023, Delaware is served exclusively by Avelo Airlines out of Wilmington Airport, launching five routes to Florida on February 1.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] This put an end to an eight-month period during which Delaware had no scheduled air service, one of several since 1991.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Various airlines had served Wilmington Airport, the latest departure being Frontier Airlines in June 2022.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Delaware is centrally situated in the Northeast megalopolis region of cities along I-95.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Therefore, Delaware commercial airline passengers most frequently use Philadelphia International Airport (PHL), Baltimore-Washington International Thurgood Marshall Airport (BWI) and Washington Dulles International Airport (IAD) for domestic and international transit.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Residents of Sussex County will also use Wicomico Regional Airport (SBY), as it is located less than 10 miles (16 km) from the Delaware border.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Atlantic City International Airport (ACY), Newark Liberty International Airport (EWR), and Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport (DCA) are also within a 100-mile (160 km) radius of New Castle County.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Other general aviation airports in Delaware include Summit Airport near Middletown, Delaware Airpark near Cheswold, and Delaware Coastal Airport near Georgetown.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Dover Air Force Base, one of the largest in the country, is home to the 436th Airlift Wing and the 512th Airlift Wing.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] In addition to its other responsibilities in the Air Mobility Command, it serves as the entry point and mortuary for U.S. military personnel (and some civilians) who die overseas.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Delaware's fourth and current constitution, adopted in 1897, provides for executive, judicial and legislative branches.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The Delaware General Assembly consists of a House of Representatives with 41 members and a Senate with 21 members.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Representatives are elected to two-year terms, while senators are elected to four-year terms.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The Senate confirms judicial and other nominees appointed by the governor.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Senators are Lisa Blunt Rochester (Democrat) and Chris Coons (Democrat).
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Representative is Sarah McBride (Democrat).
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Minor non-constitutional courts include the Justice of the Peace Courts and Aldermen's Courts.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Significantly, Delaware has one of the few remaining Courts of Chancery in the nation, which has jurisdiction over equity cases, the vast majority of which are corporate disputes, many relating to mergers and acquisitions.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The Court of Chancery and the Delaware Supreme Court have developed a worldwide reputation for rendering concise opinions concerning corporate law which generally (but not always) grant broad discretion to corporate boards of directors and officers.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] In addition, the Delaware General Corporation Law, which forms the basis of the Courts' opinions, is widely regarded as giving great flexibility to corporations to manage their affairs.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] For these reasons, Delaware is considered to have the most business-friendly legal system in the United States; therefore a great number of companies are incorporated in Delaware, including 60% of the companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Delaware was the last U.S. state to use judicial corporal punishment, in 1952.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The executive branch is headed by the Governor of Delaware.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The current governor is Matt Meyer (Democrat), who took office January 21, 2025.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The lieutenant governor is Kyle Evans Gay.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The governor presents a "State of the State" speech to a joint session of the Delaware legislature annually.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The executive branch also consists of the Attorney General of Delaware currently held by Kathy Jennings, the State Treasurer currently held by Colleen Davis, the Auditor of Accounts currently held by Lydia York and the Insurance Commissioner currently held by Trinidad Navarro.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Delaware is subdivided into three counties; from north to south they are New Castle, Kent and Sussex.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Each county elects its own legislative body (known in New Castle and Sussex counties as **County Council**, and in Kent County as **Levy Court**), which deal primarily in zoning and development issues.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Most functions which are handled on a county-by-county basis in other states—such as court and law enforcement—have been centralized in Delaware, leading to a significant concentration of power in the Delaware state government.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The counties were historically divided into hundreds, which were used as tax reporting and voting districts until the 1960s, but now serve no administrative role, their only current official legal use being in real estate title descriptions.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The Democratic Party holds a plurality of registrations in Delaware.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Currently, Democrats hold all positions of authority in Delaware, as well as majorities in the state Senate and House.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The Democrats have held the governorship since 1993, having won the last seven gubernatorial elections.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Democrats presently hold all the nine statewide elected offices, while the Republicans last won any statewide offices in 2014, State Auditor and State Treasurer.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] During the First and Second Party Systems, Delaware was a stronghold for the Federalist and Whig Parties, respectively.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] After a relatively brief adherence to the Democratic Solid South following the US Civil War, Delaware became a Republican-leaning state from 1896 through 1948, voting for losing Republicans Charles Evans Hughes in 1916, Herbert Hoover in 1932, and Thomas Dewey in 1948.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] During the second half of the 20th century, Delaware was a bellwether state, voting for the winner of every presidential election from 1952 through 1996.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Delaware's bellwether status came to an end when Delaware voted for Al Gore in 2000 by 13%.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] In 2020, Delaware native (and Barack Obama's former vice president and running mate) Joe Biden headed the Democratic ticket; he carried his home state by just shy of 19% en route to a national 4.5% win.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The dominant factor in Delaware's political shift has been the strong Democratic trend in heavily urbanized New Castle County, home to 55% of Delaware's population.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] New Castle County has not voted Republican in a presidential election since 1988, and has given Democrats over 60% of its vote in every election from 2004 on.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] In 1992, 2000, 2004, and 2016, the Republican presidential candidate carried both Kent and Sussex but lost by double digits each time in New Castle County, which was a large enough margin to tip the state to the Democrats.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] New Castle County also elects a substantial majority of the state legislature; 27 of the 41 state house districts and 14 of the 21 state senate districts are based in New Castle County.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] In a 2020 study, Delaware was ranked as the 18th hardest state for citizens to vote in.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Each of the 50 states of the United States has passed some form of freedom of information legislation, which provides a mechanism for the general public to request information of the government.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] In 2011 Delaware passed legislation placing a 15 business day time limit on addressing freedom-of-information requests, to either produce information or an explanation of why such information would take longer than this time to produce.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] A bill aimed at restricting Freedom of Information Act requests, Senate Bill 155, was discussed in committee.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Tax is collected by the Delaware Division of Revenue.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Delaware has six different income tax brackets, ranging from 2.2% to 5.95%.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The state does not assess sales tax on consumers.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The state does, however, impose a tax on the gross receipts of most businesses.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Business and occupational license tax rates range from 0.096% to 1.92%, depending on the category of business activity.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Delaware does not assess a state-level tax on real or personal property.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Real estate is subject to county property taxes, school district property taxes, vocational school district taxes, and, if located within an incorporated area, municipal property taxes.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Gambling provides significant revenue to the state.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] For instance, the casino at Delaware Park Racetrack provided more than $100 million to the state in 2010.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] In June 2018, Delaware became the first U.S. state to legalize sports betting following the Supreme Court ruling to overturn the Professional and Amateur Sports Protection Act of 1992 (PASPA).
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] As Delaware has no franchises in the major American professional sports leagues, many Delawareans follow either Philadelphia or Baltimore teams.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] In the WNBA, the Washington Mystics enjoy a major following due to the presence of Wilmington native and University of Delaware product Elena Delle Donne.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] The University of Delaware's football team has a large following throughout the state, with the Delaware State University and Wesley College teams also enjoying a smaller degree of support.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Delaware is home to Dover Motor Speedway and Bally's Dover.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Dover Motor Speedway, also known as the *Monster Mile*, is one of only 10 tracks in the nation to have hosted 100 or more NASCAR Cup Series races.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Bally's Dover is a popular harness racing facility.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] It is the only co-located horse- and car-racing facility in the nation, with the Bally's Dover track located inside the Dover Motor Speedway track.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Delaware is represented in rugby by the Delaware Black Foxes, a 2015 expansion club.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Delaware has been home to two professional wrestling outfits: Combat Zone Wrestling (CZW) and its Tournament of Death, and ECWA with its annual Super 8 Tournament.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Delaware's official state sport is bicycling.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Delaware has had a foreign sister state in Japan, named Miyagi Prefecture.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] These two have shared relations since 1997, and have had exchange programs available for students that were briefly paused in wake of the earthquake and the tsunami that ensued in the prefecture during March 2011.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Prominent Delawareans include the du Pont family of politicians and businesspersons, and the 46th president of the United States Joe Biden.
[src:delaware/delaware-p02] Biden's family moved to Delaware during his childhood, and he later represented Delaware for 36 years in the United States Senate from 1973 to 2009, before becoming 47th vice president of the United States from 2009 to 2017.
